### Adaptations and Sequels of His Works

Hilton's novels proved fertile ground for filmmakers.

*   [ *Lost Horizon* ](/Lost_Horizon) was adapted multiple times, in [1937](/Lost_Horizon_(1937_film)) and again in [1973](/Lost_Horizon_(1973_film)).
*   [ *Knight Without Armour* ](/Knight_Without_Armour) found its cinematic form in 1937.
*   [ *We Are Not Alone* ](/We_Are_Not_Alone_(1939_film)) was brought to the screen in 1939, with Hilton himself contributing to the screenplay.
*   [ *Goodbye, Mr. Chips* ](/Goodbye,_Mr._Chips) has had a remarkable afterlife on film, with adaptations in [1939](/Goodbye,_Mr._Chips_(1939_film)), [1969](/Goodbye,_Mr._Chips_(1969_film)), 1984, and 2002.
*   [ *Rage in Heaven* ](/Rage_in_Heaven) was filmed in 1941.
*   [ *Random Harvest* ](/Random_Harvest_(film)) became a cinematic hit in 1942, and was later reprised on radio in 1943.
*   [ *The Story of Dr. Wassell* ](/The_Story_of_Dr._Wassell), starring Gary Cooper, was released in 1944.
*   [ *So Well Remembered* ](/So_Well_Remembered) was adapted in 1947, featuring [John Mills](/John_Mills) and narrated by Hilton himself.

Hilton also co-wrote the book and lyrics for [ *Shangri-La* ](/Shangri-La_(musical)), a musical adaptation of *Lost Horizon* that, regrettably, proved to be a spectacular Broadway failure in 1956.

The tale of Shangri-La was revisited by Eleanor Cooney and Daniel Altieri in their 2004 novel *Shangri-La*. Licensed by [William Morrow](/William_Morrow_and_Company) (an imprint of [HarperCollins](/HarperCollins)) and approved by Hilton's heirs, this sequel followed the story into the tumultuous [Cultural Revolution](/Cultural_Revolution) of the 1960s, before flashing back to the 1930s. It garnered international publication and was recognized as a *New York Times* Notable Book.

### Memorials

The placement of a [blue plaque](/Blue_plaque) in honor of Hilton became a point of contention in the late 1990s. [Wigan Council](/Wigan_Metropolitan_Borough_Council), the local authority for Leigh, initially proposed placing it on the town hall, rather than on his birthplace at 26 Wilkinson Street. This sparked considerable debate among the residents of Leigh, who felt the birthplace was the more appropriate location. Ultimately, in 2013, a blue plaque was affixed to his actual birthplace.

In 1997, another blue plaque was erected on the wall of 42 Oakhill Gardens, [Woodford Green](/Woodford_Green). This modest semi-detached house was where Hilton lived with his parents from 1921, a quiet backdrop to the creation of his most famous worlds.

It's important to distinguish this James Hilton from another prominent figure in Leigh: a businessman who became chairman of [Leigh Rugby League Football Club](/Leigh_Centurions) after the war. The club's former ground, [Hilton Park](/Hilton_Park_(stadium)), was named in his honor.

